# Web Accessibility Standards (WCAG AA)

All public-facing web UI must meet **WCAG AA** standards. Minimum contrast ratio: **4.5:1** for normal text, **3:1** for large text (18pt+ or 14pt+ bold).

## Color Contrast Requirements

### Light Backgrounds (white, stone-50, stone-100)

| Color Class | Contrast Ratio | Status |
|---|---|---|
| `text-stone-300` | 2.1:1 | ❌ FAILS — never use |
| `text-stone-400` | 2.6:1 | ❌ FAILS — never use |
| `text-stone-500` | 4.6:1 | ✅ PASSES — minimum safe |
| `text-stone-600` | 5.9:1 | ✅ PASSES — preferred |
| `text-stone-700` | 8.1:1 | ✅ PASSES AAA — use for emphasis |
| `text-stone-900` | 16.1:1 | ✅ PASSES AAA — use for headlines |

**Safe choices:** `text-stone-600` for body, `text-stone-700` for labels, `text-slate-900` for headlines.

### Dark Backgrounds (slate-900, slate-800)

| Color Class | Contrast Ratio | Status |
|---|---|---|
| `text-white/30` | 1.9:1 | ❌ FAILS — never use |
| `text-white/50` | 3.2:1 | ❌ FAILS — never use |
| `text-white/55` | 3.6:1 | ❌ FAILS — never use |
| `text-white/60` | 4.1:1 | ⚠️ MARGINAL — avoid |
| `text-white/70` | 5.4:1 | ✅ PASSES — minimum safe |
| `text-white/90` | 15.1:1 | ✅ PASSES AAA — preferred |
| `text-white` | 17.1:1 | ✅ PASSES AAA |
| `text-stone-200` | 13.4:1 | ✅ PASSES AAA |

**Safe choices:** `text-white/90` for body on dark, `text-white` for headlines, `text-stone-200` for muted text.

## Common Violations to Fix

### ❌ Before (FAILS)
```tsx
<div className="bg-slate-900">
  <p className="text-white/50">This fails contrast.</p>
  <span className="text-white/30">So does this.</span>
</div>

<div className="bg-white">
  <p className="text-stone-400">Also fails.</p>
</div>
```

### ✅ After (PASSES)
```tsx
<div className="bg-slate-900">
  <p className="text-white/90">This passes AAA.</p>
  <span className="text-white/70">Minimum safe.</span>
</div>

<div className="bg-white">
  <p className="text-stone-600">Now compliant.</p>
</div>
```

## Verification Checklist

When adding or editing visible text:

1. **Identify background color** — light (white/stone) or dark (slate-900)?
2. **Check text color against the table above** — does it pass?
3. **If marginal or failing** — upgrade to the next safe tier
4. **Test locally** — build and visually inspect before pushing
5. **Tools:** Browser DevTools Lighthouse audit or WebAIM contrast checker

## Special Cases

- **Disabled states:** `text-stone-400` is acceptable on light backgrounds for disabled UI elements only
- **Placeholder text:** Can be slightly lower contrast (4.5:1 not required), but still prefer `text-stone-500`
- **Focus indicators:** Must have 3:1 contrast against adjacent colors (focus rings, borders)

## Quick Reference

| Background | Body Text | Labels/Emphasis | Headlines |
|---|---|---|---|
| White/stone-50 | `text-stone-600` | `text-stone-700` | `text-slate-900` |
| slate-900 | `text-white/90` | `text-white` | `text-white` |
| Primary brand colors | Test case-by-case | Test case-by-case | Test case-by-case |

## Why This Matters

- **Legal compliance:** Many jurisdictions require WCAG AA for commercial sites
- **Better UX:** Higher contrast is easier to read for everyone, not just users with vision impairments
- **Professional credibility:** Poor contrast signals careless design

## Testing Command

```bash
npm run build  # Must pass before pushing
```

Lighthouse accessibility audit in Chrome DevTools will flag contrast violations automatically.
